    <h1>8.1.11 Recalculation when DAD changes</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h2 id=3D"id-8.1.11RecalculationwhenDADchanges-Introduction&amp;Pro=
blemstatement">Introduction &amp; Problem statement</h2>
<p>Initially the requirement was made that upon any change the DAD is recal=
culated fully. A part of this calculation is the transmission of messages (=
eg emails, webnotifications).&nbsp;</p>
<p>These messages are usually used to notify people something went wrong or=
 to periodically send a report.&nbsp;</p>
<p>In the future, it will also be possible to send HTTP requests through th=
e DAE. Depending on the use case, this either should or should not happen f=
or historic events.</p>
<p>A scenario in which this should happen is one where some data is written=
 to an external database. A change in the algorithm means the new data shou=
ld be provided to the external database.&nbsp;</p>
<p>A scenario in which HTTP requests should not be repeated is one where me=
asurements are used to drive some real-life motor. For example, putting up =
the blinds when the sun is out. There's no point in doing this for historic=
 data.&nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"id-8.1.11RecalculationwhenDADchanges-Generalissue">General issue<=
/h2>
<p>A serious issue with this entire analysis is that when a user opts to re=
send, he may as well click an option reading "annihilate my quotums". Becau=
se resending messages that are usually sent over years and years in a few m=
inutes is pretty much guaranteed to exceed all quotums. Meaning that the mo=
st recent messages (usually most relevant) will not arrive for that user.&n=
bsp;</p>
<p>We will therefore recommend that the default is&nbsp;<em>not</em> to res=
end. Only in exceptional situations should the user resend.&nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"id-8.1.11RecalculationwhenDADchanges-Fromwhentostartsendingagain"=
>From when to start sending again</h2>
<p>At some point we will have to start sending messages again. There are se=
veral points in time when we can do that:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>When the current iteration record time &gt; processedUpto time for the =
previous version of the DAD</li>
<li>When the current iteration record time &gt; wall clock time used for pu=
blishing</li>
</ul>
<p>The second option is dangerous because a device's clock may be off by a =
lot. And if it is, users will not receive any (potentially important) alert=
s. We therefor recommend the first option.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Note that devices that suddenly skip back in time will still break thing=
s, but that is to be expected in a time series database.</p>
<h2 id=3D"id-8.1.11RecalculationwhenDADchanges-Possibilities">Possibilities=
</h2>
<h3 id=3D"id-8.1.11RecalculationwhenDADchanges-Userinterface">User interfac=
e</h3>
<p>The most obvious method would be to prompt the user when he publishes a =
new version whether or not he wants to&nbsp;</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>resend notifications</li>
<li>resend emails</li>
<li>re-execute HTTP requests</li>
</ul>
<p>This can be shown using checkboxes.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Advantages:</p>
<p>&nbsp;- User thinks about whether or not to send each and every time</p>
<p>Disadvantages:</p>
<p>&nbsp;- User&nbsp;<em>has</em> to think about it every time.&nbsp;<br>&n=
bsp;- Need to explain to users that this is something which has negative co=
nsequences. Not a good idea to put a whole block of text in an alert, but s=
ome explanation should be given.&nbsp;</p>
<p>We can make this option more user friendly by detecting if the old state=
ment contains any notifications/emails/http requests and to only show the p=
rompt if it does (and only with the relevant checkboxes).&nbsp;</p>
<h3 id=3D"id-8.1.11RecalculationwhenDADchanges-OptioninRASQL">Option in RAS=
QL</h3>
<p>Another option would be to add a clause to RASQL, something like&nbsp;</=
p>
<p>WITH ASSET(1) as a<br>DEFINE EVERY(a.prop) as prop<br>WHEN TRUE THEN EMA=
IL('templ')<br>RESEND (EMAIL, WEBNOTIFICATION)</p>
<p>Advantages:<br>- Users normally don't need to know about this. So they'r=
e not bothered by it unless necessary.&nbsp;<br><br>Disadvantages:<br>&nbsp=
;- Adds to language syntax (not much work, but clutters up the grammar)</p>
<h1 id=3D"id-8.1.11RecalculationwhenDADchanges-Recommendation"><s>Recommend=
ation</s></h1>
<p><s>The author recommends the RASQL option. The default will be not to re=
send any actions. When the user specifies the RESEND option, only the given=
 parameters will be resent from the beginning.&nbsp;</s></p>
<p><br></p>
